  "text": "Our results are consistent with the hypothesis that chronic hibernating myocardium represents an adaptive state where function and metabolism are downregulated to limit the development of metabolic ischemia in response to submaximal increases in the external determinants of myocardial workload. Thus, while blood flow is reduced at rest and the difference in perfusion between normal and hibernating myocardium increases during stress, it is not truly an ischemic state. An adaptive uncoupling between perfusion, metabolism, and function may be responsible for the lack of progressive functional and pathological deterioration of hibernating myocardium. [CITATION_1] ",
